# TypeScript Standards

Language-specific rules. General principles live in `coding-best-practices.mdc` — do not restate them here.

## tsconfig

- Always enable `strict`. Also enable `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` and `noFallthroughCasesInSwitch`.
- Treat compiler errors as build failures. Do not silence with `// @ts-ignore`; if a workaround is unavoidable, use `// @ts-expect-error` with a reason.

## Type Safety

- Don't use `any` — use `unknown` when the type is genuinely unknown.
- Avoid non-null assertions (`!`); narrow the type instead.
- Avoid type casts (`as Foo`); use type guards or schema parsing.
- Use `readonly` for data that shouldn't be mutated.

## type vs interface

- Prefer `interface` for object shapes.
- Use `type` only when `interface` can't express what you need: unions, intersections, mapped or conditional types, function or tuple aliases.

## Enums

- Use `enum` for fixed sets of named values.
- Prefer string enums for stable wire/log values:

```ts
enum Status {
  Idle = "idle",
  Loading = "loading",
  Done = "done",
}
```

- Avoid `const enum` — it doesn't play well with `isolatedModules` and bundlers.

## Generics

- Constrain generics with `extends` whenever you assume shape; don't leave them unbounded.
- Name generics meaningfully when more than one: `TItem`, `TKey`, `TValue`. Single `T` is fine for trivially generic helpers.
- Provide sensible defaults to keep callsites short.

## Imports & Exports

- Named exports only; no `default` exports.
- Use `import type { ... }` for type-only imports so they're erased at runtime.
- Match the project's ESM path style (e.g. `.js` extensions when required by the resolver).
- Each module exposes its public API through an `index.ts` barrel file.
- Code outside a module imports only from that module's `index.ts`, never from internal files directly.
- `index.ts` re-exports only what is intended for external use; internal helpers, types, and constants stay private to the module.

## Async

- Always `await` or explicitly handle promises; never leave them floating.
- Use `Promise.all` / `Promise.allSettled` for independent parallel work.
- Type non-trivial async returns explicitly: `async function load(): Promise<User>`.

## Errors

- In `catch`, the caught value is `unknown` — narrow before use.
- Extend `Error`, set `name`, and forward the underlying cause via `{ cause }`.

```ts
class HttpError extends Error {
  constructor(public status: number, message: string, options?: ErrorOptions) {
    super(message, options);
    this.name = "HttpError";
  }
}
```

## Zod Schemas

- Use Zod for every external boundary (HTTP, env, files, IPC).
- Derive types from schemas: `type User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>`.
- Schema is the single source of truth — do not hand-maintain a parallel `interface` for the same data.

## Naming

- `PascalCase`: types, interfaces, classes, enums, enum members.
- `camelCase`: variables, functions, methods, parameters.
- `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`: only true compile-time constants (env keys, hard limits).
- Generic params: `T`, or `TItem` / `TKey` / `TValue` when more than one.

## Style

- Prefer `const`; use `let` only when reassignment is genuine; never `var`.
- Pick one of `T[]` or `Array<T>` and stay consistent within a file (`T[]` for simple, `Array<T>` for complex generics is a common split).
- Pick one of `null` or `undefined` per codebase for "missing value"; don't use both interchangeably.
